  "prompt": "What happens to the bond between atoms in a metals when they are melted?",
  "response": "When metals are melted, the bonds between the atoms are affected significantly. In the solid state, metal atoms are arranged in a highly ordered lattice structure, and the atoms are held together by metallic bonds. Metallic bonds are characterized by a \"sea of electrons\" that are delocalized and free to move throughout the lattice, which facilitates the conduction of electricity and heat.\n\nUpon melting, the metal absorbs sufficient thermal energy to overcome the metallic bonds that hold the atoms in their fixed positions within the crystalline structure. As a result, the orderly lattice breaks down, and the metal transitions into a liquid state. In this liquid state, the atoms are no longer arranged in a fixed pattern; they become more randomly distributed and can move freely relative to one another. However, even in the liquid state, there are still attractive forces between the atoms that prevent them from completely separating; these forces are responsible for maintaining the cohesion and fluidity of the molten metal.\n\nTherefore, while the metallic bonds are not completely broken, they are significantly weakened, allowing the atoms to move more freely and the metal to take on the properties of a liquid.",
